author: @versatil2715
text: üéØ Key Takeaways for quick navigation:  Sublime Text is a popular text editor for coding, and it can be used for Python development. Sublime Text is available for free, but purchasing a license is encouraged to support the developers. The video demonstrates setting up a Python development environment in Sublime Text. Key packages for Python development in Sublime Text include Package Control for managing extensions, Bracket Highlighter for managing brackets, Sidebar Enhancements for enhancing the sidebar, and Anaconda for Python-specific features like linting and auto-formatting. Customizing settings in Sublime Text, such as themes, color schemes, and font preferences, can enhance the coding experience. Build systems in Sublime Text allow you to run and configure different versions of Python for your projects, and they should be set up according to your needs. Python 2.7 and Python 3.5 build systems can be created by defining their paths in Sublime Text's build system settings. Sublime Text may display pop-ups encouraging users to purchase a license, but it can still be used for an unlimited time without purchasing one. Python 2.7 and Python 3.5 build systems can be set up in Sublime Text to run code with different Python versions. Removing unwanted packages in Sublime Text is possible through the command palette using the "remove package" option. The video offers personalized Python development environment setup in Sublime Text, including package installation and build system configuration. The presenter mentions having similar tutorials for Atom, another code editor, which is free and user-friendly, making it a good option for beginners. The choice between Sublime Text and Atom ultimately depends on personal preferences and needs.  Made with HARPA AI

author: @sarys73
text: Corey would you please show my how to add to your settings this issue I'm having. I want to remove auto complete when I click the enter key. I've been googling and this was the option I wanted, but when I add it to the end of the settings it doesn't actually do what it's suppose to do. I still have the same issue after rebooting Sublime.     My solution to this problem was to change "auto_complete_commit_on_tab" from true to false. This way you aren't turning off autocomplete altogether, but the autocompletion is ignored unless you hit the tab key.  In preferences, user settings, add:  { "auto_complete_commit_on_tab": false }  I even tried this      "auto_complete": false,     "auto_complete_commit_on_tab": false,     "auto_close_tags":false,     "auto_match_enabled": false  UPDATE: never mind. The first option was correct with the exception that the guy who posted typed False instead of True. When I did oposite of what he suggested, it did just what I needed it to do.

author: @Neithan007
text: In Windows:  1) Go to Tools > Build System > New Build system. 2) Paste the following, editing the path for your specific case (and notice the double "\\":  {     "cmd": ["C:\\Users\\NathaN\\AppData\\Local\\Programs\\Python\\Python38-32\\Python.exe", "-u", "$file"],     "file_regex": "^[ ]*File \"(...*?)\", line ([0-9]*)",     "quiet": true }  3) control +s to save as "Python3.8.sublime-build" 4) now open a new file and write "print("Hello World") 5) File > save as > Hello_World.py 6) Tools > Build system > Python3.8 7) "Control + b" should now run your Hello world program

text: IF YOU COULDN'T GET THE BUILD SYSTEM TO WORK, TRY THIS!   >make new build system >paste {      "cmd":["py", "-u",  "$file"],     "path":"C:\\Python37\\python.exe",     "file_regex":"^[]File\"(...?)\",line([0-9]*)",     "selector": "source.python" } then save your code as a .py file then build   worked for me, I don't know if there is a more correct way to do this.

author: @22ttiimmeess
text: If anyone is getting a "[WinError 2] The system cannot find the file specified" issue, this comment from Corey was buried in the comments. I spent a good hour and a bit trying to figure it out. You might have to change the "\" in your file path in your command prompt to "/" when you put it in your path in your *.sublime-build file. This is what he commented:   Hi there. The PATH to Python is different in Windows than it is on a Unix-like machine. Try opening your command prompt and running Python, and then run the following code: import sys print(sys.executable)  It should show the PATH you need to put into your build system instead of the current "/usr/local/bin/python3.5"  I hope that helps!

author: @keithpeterston8556
text: ‚á®ADDITIONAL INFO: How To View Side Bar Folders in Sublime Text  Corey Schafer shows in this Video (at Timecode 12:19) the installation of a Package called "Side Bar Enhancements" which he describes in the video using the display of FOLDERS in the Sidebar.  WHAT IS NOT DESCRIBED CLEARLY is that in order to see Folders in the Sublime Text Editor you need to:  1. Click on VIEW MENU > Side Bar > View Side Bar. 2. Click on FILE > OPEN... then click on a File Folder (not a individual File), then click on OPEN.  OR OPTIONALLY...  Drag and drop the selected folder on to the "Sublime Text" window (method used in the video at Timecode 2:15 by Corey Schafer)  ‚îÅ‚îÅ‚îÅ‚îÅ‚îÅ‚îÅ‚îÅ‚îÅ‚îÅ‚îÅ‚îÅ‚îÅ‚îÅ‚îÅ‚îÅ‚îÅ‚îÅ‚îÅ‚îÅ‚îÅ‚îÅ‚îÅ‚îÅ‚îÅ‚îÅ‚îÅ‚îÅ‚îÅ‚îÅ  ‚òÖ RECOMMENDATION: Corey Schafer should place this information in the Video Description (as comments often get buried) so that others new to Sublime Text whom are following Video - step by step - will see the same thing as shown in the video.  Hope this helps someone.

author: @leeheang9784
text: Here to link Sublime Text Build system to Python 3 1. Go to Sublime Text to: Tools -> Build System -> New Build System  and put the next lines:  {     "cmd": ["python3", "-i", "-u", "$file"],     "file_regex": "^[ ]File \"(...?)\", line ([0-9]*)",     "selector": "source.python" }  Then save it with a meaningful name like: python3.sublime-build  2. Go to Tools -> Build system -> and check python3   test it with:  import sys print(sys.version)  Press: Ctrl + b

author: @scottmurphys
text: Thanks for the video, it got me started on the path of setting up Python in Sublime. However, since you use a Mac and I use a Windows PC there were a few difference not covered. These differences also seem to be hard to find on the official sites. I personally finally found what I was looking for in the comments of your previous Python post.  "Gurpreet Singh First, install anaconda for python 3.5 and in sublime text, tools, build systems, make new build system and save this to file and make the filename python.sublime-build  {     "cmd": ["C:\\Program Files\\Anaconda3\\python.exe", "-u", "$file"],     "file_regex": "^[ ]File \"(...?)\", line ([0-9]*)",     "selector": "source.python" }  it will definitely work.   Also directory can be different in your system. So to check python directory interpreter open cmd (window) [at the root] c drive level and type "where python.exe" (without the quotes)."  Personally I installed Python 2.7 and 3.6 (64). Following the above video I made two files and saved them to my "C:\Users\SMurphy\AppData\Roaming\Sublime Text 3\Packages\User" folder  and named them Python27.sublime-build and Python36-64.sublime-build respectively.  All but the path was the same as Gurpreet Singh's example.  {     "cmd": ["C:\\Program Files\\Python\\Python36\\python.exe", "-u", "$file"],     "file_regex": "^[ ]*File \"(...*?)\", line ([0-9]*)",     "quiet": true }  I hope this give Windows users one more place to chance on an answer, and thank you Cory for your help.
